                              <heading>Overview</heading>
                              <p id="CA.DIR.202403151523" usage="usac">
              
              Traditionally the daily press in Canada was essentially local in coverage, influence and distribution. In 1998 publication began of Canada's first national newspaper, the 
              <i>National Post</i>
              . A national edition of the Toronto 
              <i>Globe and Mail</i>
              , established in 1981, was also available coast to coast, as was (from 1988) a national edition of the 
              <i>Financial Post</i>
              .
            </p>
                              
                              <p id="CA.DIR.202403151524" usage="usac">Chain ownership has traditionally been predominant. In 2017 Postmedia Network Inc/Sun Media was the largest publisher by of paid daily newspapers in Canada, owing 42 such titles (in addition to two free daily newspapers. Torstar Corpn owned nine dailies (of which only three were paid publications) in 2017, followed by SaltWire Network Inc, with eight titles, and Groupe Capitales Médias, with six. There has been substantial consolidation in the sector during the 2010s, with the formerly dominant Québecor Media Inc retaining control of only three daily newspapers (two of which were paid) in 2017; TC retained control of only two daily newspapers, both free, having sold seven other publications to SaltWire Network Inc in April of that year.</p>
                              <p id="CA.DIR.202403151525" usage="ewyb usac">In 2022, there were 71 daily newspaper titles in Canada, with an average weekly circulation in total of 16.1m copies. Of this, around 10m. was paid-for and 6m. was free-to-read. In recent years an increasing number of paid-for newspapers have introduced paid access to their websites. In 2022, there were 949 community newspaper titles, serving local audiences in metropolitan areas as well as the more remote areas of the country. These newspapers had a combined circulation of around 13.4m. per week. Many community newspapers have closed down since 2020, as a result of the economic crisis linked with the COVID-19 pandemic that commenced that year.</p>
                              <p id="CA.DIR.202403151526" usage="ewyb usac">
              There are numerous periodicals for business, trade, professional, recreational and special interest readership, although periodical publishing, particularly, encounters substantial competition from publications originating in the USA. Among periodicals, the only one that could be regarded as national in its readership and coverage is the weekly news magazine 
              <i>Maclean's</i>
              .
            </p>
                              
